## Tools Used 

- SIEM, IDS/IPS, AV, EDR.
- Incident Response Playbooks and Runbooks.
- Security monitoring dashboards.
- Malware analysis and containment tools.

## Findings

- Incident Response requires structured frameworks (SANS/NIST).
- Alerts must be analyzed to distinguish false positives from true incidents.
- Incidents vary in type and severity, requiring tailored responses.
- Playbooks and runbooks streamline response and reduce errors.
- Lab exercises demonstrate real-world application of IR phases.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Implement continuous monitoring with SIEM and IDS/IPS.
- Train analysts to reduce false positives and identify true incidents.
- Classify incidents by severity to prioritize response.
- Develop and maintain Incident Response Plans and Playbooks.
- Regularly update systems to reduce malware and breach risks.
- Educate employees to prevent phishing and insider threats.
- Conduct post-incident reviews to improve processes.

## Conclusion

- Incident Response provides a comprehensive framework for managing cyber incidents.
- SANS and NIST frameworks guide organizations through structured phases.
- Tools like SIEM, AV, and EDR support detection and response.
- Playbooks and runbooks ensure consistent, efficient handling of incidents.
- Practical exercises reinforce the importance of preparation, detection, containment, eradication, recovery, and lessons learned.
